  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- International standards for preventing money laundering\n- Adopted by over 180 countries\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Provides framework for international cooperation\n- Calls for criminalizing money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision Guidelines\n- Sets standards for banking regulations\n- Helps prevent financial crimes\n\n4. The Palermo Convention\n- Focuses on preventing organized crime and money laundering\n- Adopted by the UN in 2000\n\n5. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish uniform rules for EU member states\n- Regularly updated to address emerging risks\n\nThese laws generally require:\n- Reporting suspicious financial transactions\n- Customer due diligence\n- Maintaining financial records\n- Cooperation between countries\n- Establishing legal penalties for money laundering\n\nMost countries have their own domestic laws implementing these international standards, such as the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar legislation in other nations.",
